MALE SPEAKER: Very
warm welcome.

00:00:03.870 --> 00:00:07.330
We're going to be discussing
everything monsters today.

00:00:07.330 --> 00:00:08.119
I thought I'd start--

00:00:08.119 --> 00:00:11.280
I spent the first 10 minutes
writing down some monster

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:15.840
jokes to whip you into
a monster frenzy.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:16.560
OK.

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:18.680
Why couldn't the monster
buy a pair of shoes?

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:22.310
DAN SCANLON: Why?

00:00:22.310 --> 00:00:22.840
KORI RAE: He didn't have feet.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:24.220
MALE SPEAKER: Because
he had a big foot.

00:00:24.220 --> 00:00:24.690
KORI RAE: Ah.

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:26.100
DAN SCANLON: Ah.

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:27.220
That's gold.

00:00:27.220 --> 00:00:29.022
It's not too late to get
that in the movie.

00:00:29.022 --> 00:00:31.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:33.230
MALE SPEAKER: It
does get worse.

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:37.820
Why did the monster transfer
jobs so easily?

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:38.860
DAN SCANLON: I don't know.

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:40.830
MALE SPEAKER: Because of the
claws in his contract.

00:00:40.830 --> 00:00:42.952
DAN SCANLON: Ah.

00:00:42.952 --> 00:00:44.434
MALE SPEAKER: That's
terrible, isn't it?

00:00:44.434 --> 00:00:44.930
DAN SCANLON: Much worse.

00:00:44.930 --> 00:00:46.830
KORI RAE: Nice.

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:48.130
MALE SPEAKER: Last
one, I promise.

00:00:48.130 --> 00:00:51.200
Why couldn't the monster
get into his apartment?

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:52.310
This one needs a bit of work.

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:54.170
DAN SCANLON: OK.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:54.760
KORI RAE: The others didn't.

00:00:54.760 --> 00:00:55.630
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, yeah.

00:00:55.630 --> 00:00:57.230
The others are great.

00:00:57.230 --> 00:00:58.890
MALE SPEAKER: Why couldn't
the monster--

00:00:58.890 --> 00:00:59.710
now I haven't--

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:00.600
there is a punchline.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:00.900
DAN SCANLON: OK.

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:02.000
KORI RAE: OK.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:03.550
MALE SPEAKER: He couldn't get
into his apartment because of

00:01:03.550 --> 00:01:05.650
the Lock Ness Monster.

00:01:05.650 --> 00:01:07.300
KORI RAE: Oh.

00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:08.712
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:01:08.712 --> 00:01:10.040
Except that--

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:10.690
OK.

00:01:10.690 --> 00:01:11.260
We'll work on that.

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:13.380
MALE SPEAKER: Well,
I wrote down

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:14.776
applause and I got a little.

00:01:14.776 --> 00:01:16.114
DAN SCANLON: Oh look at that.

00:01:16.114 --> 00:01:17.590
You wrote down applause.

00:01:17.590 --> 00:01:20.950
With an actual pause
for those jokes.

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:21.910
It's very professional.

00:01:21.910 --> 00:01:22.600
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:27.300
So thankfully you're not here
to listen to these jokes.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:31.080
We're actually here to meet the
creators of this, which

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:34.152
will either be awkward
silence or a trailer.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:42.690
So we're very lucky to have
the director of "Monsters

00:01:42.690 --> 00:01:46.525
University," Dan Scanlon, and
Kori Rae, the producer.

00:01:46.525 --> 00:01:47.950
KORI RAE: Hello.

00:01:47.950 --> 00:01:49.230
MALE SPEAKER: Maybe I'll ask
you to introduce a bit more

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:51.860
about yourselves in a minute,
but the first question is how

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:54.910
does it feel seeing that?

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:56.820
DAN SCANLON: Oh, it's great.

00:01:56.820 --> 00:01:59.160
It's fun to watch the trailer
with an audience.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:00.190
I don't think we've
ever done that.

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:01.280
KORI RAE: I know.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:01.640
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:04.180
We're so excited that
the movie's done.

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:06.920
We spent so much time
working on it.

00:02:06.920 --> 00:02:10.940
We spend almost five years
working on each individual

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:12.830
film at Pixar.

00:02:12.830 --> 00:02:17.490
And so to finally have the movie
coming out in two days

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:18.650
and to be able to share
it with the

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:20.210
world is very exciting.

00:02:20.210 --> 00:02:21.220
MALE SPEAKER: Wow.

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:24.410
From a production point of view,
the amount of work that

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:26.040
goes into that-- is that
a relief to see

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:27.710
how amazing it is?

00:02:27.710 --> 00:02:28.160
KORI RAE: It is.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.640
And it's been interesting
in the last few weeks.

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:33.750
It's almost bittersweet when
it's over because you do spend

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:37.180
so much time with the crew
and so much time on the

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:37.710
production.

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:41.440
And it's a little bit of an odd
departure when it's over

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:45.650
so we're still experiencing
a little bit of that.

00:02:45.650 --> 00:02:47.810
But super-excited to get
it out to the world.

00:02:47.810 --> 00:02:48.603
Can't wait.

00:02:48.603 --> 00:02:49.290
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:51.920
So we may open up some questions
we have maybe 20

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:52.560
minutes left.

00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:56.030
So I was hopefully going to
go through some topics.

00:02:56.030 --> 00:02:59.300
I was kind of interested in how
you arrived at Pixar on

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:02.780
your journey and a little bit
about your education and

00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:04.220
inspirations.

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:08.410
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, in my case
I always loved to draw, got

00:03:08.410 --> 00:03:11.820
really into film and animation
when I was young.

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:14.640
I went to college in
Ohio studying--

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:18.020
actually studying illustration
and kind of fell

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:20.290
off film for awhile.

00:03:20.290 --> 00:03:23.080
But then I get a job at this
company in Ohio called

00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:25.850
Character Builders that did a
lot of direct-to-video Disney

00:03:25.850 --> 00:03:29.420
sequels, "The Little Mermaid
II" and "101 Dalmatians II"

00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:31.220
and all those.

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:31.770
But it was great.

00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:34.390
It was a great experience
because we had to make the

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:38.980
movies for half the budget
and half the time.

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:40.730
Frankly even knowing that you're
making a movie that

00:03:40.730 --> 00:03:43.210
people didn't want to exist.

00:03:43.210 --> 00:03:45.420
The people didn't want
those movies.

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:46.160
But I liked that.

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:48.970
I liked kind of the underdog
nature of, all right we're

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:52.210
going to try to make these
as good as we can.

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:56.770
And then I left there and I
applied to as many places as I

00:03:56.770 --> 00:04:00.740
could because I just wanted to
try to move to California.

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:02.330
To try to really go for it.

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:03.840
And I applied at all these
different places.

00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:07.090
And I applied at Pixar as
sort of the joke one.

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:09.200
Like well, I guess it wouldn't
hurt to get my

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:11.400
name on a form somewhere.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.910
And no one replied to
me except for Pixar.

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:16.300
And it was such a great example

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:18.540
of just go for whatever.

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:21.510
Go for everything you want
because you never know.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:24.660
And luckily they brought me in
to work on "Cars"-- the first

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:25.740
"Cars."

00:04:25.740 --> 00:04:29.510
And in my interview with Joe
Ranft, who was a great story

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:33.330
artist there, he said, oh you're
from the Detroit area.

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:35.800
I bet you're really good
at drawing cars.

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:37.950
I didn't know what the movie
was going to be about yet.

00:04:37.950 --> 00:04:40.370
And I said, oh to be honest with
you I hate drawing cars.

00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:41.060
I don't know how to do it.

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:42.620
That's why I'm leaving
Detroit.

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:44.210
I couldn't draw a car
to save my life.

00:04:44.210 --> 00:04:48.130
And then I said, the movie's
called "Cars"?

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:49.620
I was like, ohh.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:51.940
Oh.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.470
And so, yeah "Monsters Inc," the
first one, actually came

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:56.290
out the first month that
I worked at Pixar.

00:04:56.290 --> 00:04:59.100
And I got to go to the wrap
party and it was just such a

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:00.830
dream to be there.

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:02.620
And then I worked on "Toy
Story" and made my own

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:05.620
live-action film feature
called "Tracy" on the

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:10.280
weekends, with other people from
Pixar, just as practice

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:12.520
writing and directing
a feature on my own.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:15.030
And I think that helped
me get this job.

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:16.290
MALE SPEAKER: So the inspiration
was Disney when

00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:18.010
you were a child--

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:20.220
sort of growing up with the old
classic [INAUDIBLE] films.

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:22.470
DAN SCANLON: A lot of it was
more Warner Bros., Chuck

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:24.180
Jones, Tex Avery-- that
kind of stuff.

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.900
But I was a fan of the shorts
Pixar was doing.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:29.070
And I was a fan of Aardman, the
shorts that Aardman was

00:05:29.070 --> 00:05:31.060
doing at the time.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:32.210
MALE SPEAKER: That's great.

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:34.880
And Kori, in terms of producing,
did you start small

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:36.560
and then work into
big scale film?

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:39.180
KORI RAE: Yeah, I started
at the very bottom.

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:44.530
I got in on the ground floor
about 20 years ago when we

00:05:44.530 --> 00:05:46.920
used to produce commercials.

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:51.320
And I applied for an assistant
to the executive producer of

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:54.860
the Commercials Group and went
up against a couple of

00:05:54.860 --> 00:05:55.670
internal people.

00:05:55.670 --> 00:05:58.520
And I had a little bit of a
writing background and project

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:01.400
management background, so
somehow they hired me.

00:06:01.400 --> 00:06:06.150
And then I kind of quickly
worked my way up in the

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:10.070
Commercial Group and started
producing commercials until

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:11.470
"Toy Story" came out.

00:06:11.470 --> 00:06:14.540
And they took all of our
people that were in the

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:17.420
Commercials Group, all 12 or
13, just to finish "Toy

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:22.770
Story." And then once it was
released and Disney said well

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:24.750
maybe we might help--

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:27.800
if you want to make another
movie, maybe.

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:30.120
So that's when we kind of
closed up shop in the

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:33.770
Commercial Group and I moved
over and started working on "A

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:35.910
Bug's Life" as the animation
manager.

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:38.080
So that was my first
feature film.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:41.410
And then I've worked on a bunch
since then, and this is

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:42.780
my first full producing gig.

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:45.230
I was a development producer
on "Up" but just

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:47.960
for the first year.

00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:50.990
MALE SPEAKER: What's really
astounding I think, watching

00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:54.200
Pixar movies, is the incredible
amount of detail

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:56.440
and love and passion that
goes into those films.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.180
And also how complex it must
be from the beginning of a

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:01.950
storyboard through to
the finished piece.

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:04.590
But just a little bit on that
process, do you still

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.010
traditionally begin with the
drawings and the gag drawings

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.690
the way that the old Disney
films were made and the old

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:10.510
Warner Bros. films?

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:10.980
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:11.270
KORI RAE: Yeah.

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:11.560
DAN SCANLON: Absolutely.

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:12.330
KORI RAE: Absolutely, yeah.

00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:16.410
We did over 200,000 storyboards
for this film.

00:07:16.410 --> 00:07:17.550
So--

00:07:17.550 --> 00:07:17.910
DAN SCANLON: Oops.

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:20.435
KORI RAE: For better or worse.

00:07:20.435 --> 00:07:22.960
DAN SCANLON: I couldn't
make up my mind.

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:25.300
Yeah, we'd still do a ton
of hand-drawn stuff.

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:26.230
Even our storyboards--

00:07:26.230 --> 00:07:28.730
and when I started on "Cars"
our storyboards were

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:32.560
completely hand-drawn on paper
and pasted to the wall, and we

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:34.790
pointed at them with
an old stick.

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:38.860
It feels like an incredibly
outdated thing now, but the

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:40.000
world changed fast.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.540
And now we're drawing
on Cintiqs.

00:07:44.540 --> 00:07:47.360
But you know in the art
department people still draw

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:49.100
on paper every now and then.

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:50.432
KORI RAE: Yep.

00:07:50.432 --> 00:07:51.320
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:54.130
MALE SPEAKER: And I guess
because the actual process of

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:58.330
these animation renderings is
very expensive, you really try

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:00.450
and get the lock down
on these finished

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:01.550
animatics to begin with.

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:04.070
So you've pretty much got the
whole story working before you

00:08:04.070 --> 00:08:05.240
move forward.

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:06.550
KORI RAE: At least
segments of it.

00:08:06.550 --> 00:08:07.130
You know what I mean.

00:08:07.130 --> 00:08:11.380
We certainly put the story reels
up over and over again a

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:13.600
lot the first two
years at least--

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:14.400
like every three months.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:17.090
We'd put them, up we show
them to the internal

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:18.930
kind of brain trust--

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:20.320
all the directors at Pixar.

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:23.070
Then they give a bunch of notes,
we tear them down and

00:08:23.070 --> 00:08:23.780
we start all over.

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:27.820
And we do that every
three months or so.

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:30.900
And then slowly we--

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:32.429
and along with that
we do design.

00:08:32.429 --> 00:08:34.870
We start design pretty
early-on as well--

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:35.890
production design.

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:38.189
And then it kind of gets into
production from there.

00:08:38.189 --> 00:08:39.530
MALE SPEAKER: So you're kind of
building everything up bit

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:41.834
by bit, but occasionally
going back in.

00:08:41.834 --> 00:08:43.830
KORI RAE: Yeah, for sure.

00:08:43.830 --> 00:08:45.790
MALE SPEAKER: So I guess you
took this template but then

00:08:45.790 --> 00:08:49.600
you also thought we want this
idea for a sequel, but we

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:51.640
don't want a sequel
we want a prequel.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:53.836
How did that come about?

00:08:53.836 --> 00:08:56.200
DAN SCANLON: About five years
ago we started thinking about

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:57.450
it for the first time.

00:08:57.450 --> 00:09:00.180
Just the idea that we loved
these characters and wanted to

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:04.550
see if there was even an
idea there worth doing.

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:08.560
So a bunch of us got together,
including John Lasseter and

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:10.510
Pete Docter who wrote the
original-- or I mean that

00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:12.380
directed the original film--

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:14.810
the original writers
were there.

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:18.680
And we thought if we were going
to do a story with these

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:21.140
characters we wanted to do
something that explored their

00:09:21.140 --> 00:09:22.940
relationship more.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:25.500
And that was really where we got
the idea of well we should

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:27.180
go back in time and actually
see how the

00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:30.290
relationship developed.

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:34.140
And obviously from that idea
we loved the entertainment

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:36.960
possibility of college,
monster college.

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:40.260
But the real heart of it for
us was when we realized we

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:41.940
could tell the story
about Mike.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:46.790
And the movie is very
much Mike's story.

00:09:46.790 --> 00:09:49.070
It's a movie about these guys
coming together but our main

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:50.970
character this time is Mike.

00:09:50.970 --> 00:09:56.180
And we found that prequels are
tough because you more or less

00:09:56.180 --> 00:09:58.330
know how the movie's going to
end and that everyone's going

00:09:58.330 --> 00:09:59.580
to survive.

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:03.570
And so we wanted to tell a story
where knowing the ending

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:05.710
at the beginning of the movie
was a good thing.

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:09.020
We wanted to tell a story about
a character who doesn't

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:10.820
get everything he wants
in the end.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:14.220
There are so many movies that
say if you work hard and never

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:17.910
give up everything will
always turn out great.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:20.310
And even though that's a great
message it's just sadly it's

00:10:20.310 --> 00:10:21.540
not always true.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:24.160
And so many of us that
experienced that in our weird

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:28.380
past to our careers, that we'd
had these big dreams that were

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:29.340
kind of dashed.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.620
And at the time it seemed
devastating, but we look back

00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:33.700
on it now and realize
well it actually led

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:34.720
to something better.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:36.130
And we wanted to tell
that story.

00:10:36.130 --> 00:10:40.520
So it's really the story of Mike
desperately wanting to be

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:42.760
a scarer more than anything
in his life.

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:45.570
And then the audience
knowing he's headed

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:47.390
for kind of a disaster.

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:48.900
That seemed so interesting
to us.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:52.170
To tell a story that was a
little controversial and we

00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:54.340
hadn't quite seen before.

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:56.800
And that's where the gist
of the idea came from.

00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:58.700
MALE SPEAKER: It was sort of a
wonderful surprise watching

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:01.860
the film thinking that
we do know, kind of

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:02.840
in a way, what happens.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:05.320
But actually it's just
this great snapshot

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:06.880
of life on an American--

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:09.490
in an American university.

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:12.440
