00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:19.370
It's almost like--

00:16:19.370 --> 00:16:19.900
that's incredible.

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:24.100
I mean how far can that
technology go?

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:24.850
DAN SCANLON: I don't know.

00:16:24.850 --> 00:16:25.270
KORI RAE: I don't know.

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:25.980
It's amazing.

00:16:25.980 --> 00:16:30.690
I think it's that the artists
are really pushing themselves

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:31.190
all the time.

00:16:31.190 --> 00:16:32.390
This isn't like Dan--

00:16:32.390 --> 00:16:34.840
I don't think Dan was in the
review going, OK now make sure

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.850
that that marker really
seeps in there.

00:16:37.850 --> 00:16:40.040
It's everybody challenging
themselves.

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:40.840
And that's--

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:44.470
like this environment, it's
similar at Pixar--

00:16:44.470 --> 00:16:47.840
we're just always trying
to push individually.

00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:50.420
All the artists are pushing
themselves to do something

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:51.560
cooler than last time.

00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:55.300
Or add that little touch at
the very end of the shot.

00:16:55.300 --> 00:16:56.340
And it's remarkable.

00:16:56.340 --> 00:17:00.170
