00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:26.100
It's not a joke.

00:20:26.100 --> 00:20:26.820
No more jokes.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:31.270
But I mean you're a director
of the most successful film

00:20:31.270 --> 00:20:35.221
company in history.

00:20:35.221 --> 00:20:38.120
Is there a level of--

00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:42.270
is there a level of pressure
that you feel?

00:20:42.270 --> 00:20:44.000
DAN SCANLON: I think that we--

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.070
we're pretty supported
at Pixar.

00:20:46.070 --> 00:20:48.120
It's a very supportive place.

00:20:48.120 --> 00:20:51.780
I always feel like we're
all in it together.

00:20:51.780 --> 00:20:53.790
It's not competitive you know.

00:20:53.790 --> 00:20:57.910
We try not to look at our movies
next to the other one

00:20:57.910 --> 00:20:59.270
and that type of thing.

00:20:59.270 --> 00:21:03.330
Everyone is so excited about
whatever individual movie is

00:21:03.330 --> 00:21:04.370
coming out that you--

00:21:04.370 --> 00:21:08.000
I don't know-- you really don't
think about it as much.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.035
I think we're trying to make
movies that we like.

00:21:12.035 --> 00:21:14.550
Because at first, our first
audience is ourselves.

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:15.360
It's the company.

00:21:15.360 --> 00:21:18.780
And we're trying to make
a movie that we like.

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:21.230
And we honestly believe and
hope that if we do that,

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:24.060
hopefully we'll connect with
people rather than trying to

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:27.080
judge what the world
wants right now.

00:21:27.080 --> 00:21:32.050
I think that's always kind of
a dangerous road to go down.

00:21:32.050 --> 00:21:33.990
But I don't know.

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:35.440
Everyone keeps asking me if
I feel this pressure.

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:37.770
I feel like I should
probably feel it.

00:21:37.770 --> 00:21:40.290
I do now.

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:42.030
KORI RAE: I think part of it
is that there's pressure at

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:44.490
the beginning in it because it's
just getting the story

00:21:44.490 --> 00:21:46.070
off the ground in any
way shape or form

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:47.010
is the hardest part.

00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:48.240
And then there's no time.

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:50.710
There's no time to think if
you're really moving forward.

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:52.970
There's no time to even think
about the pressure.

00:21:52.970 --> 00:21:57.700
It's so crazy how jam packed the
production schedule is--

00:21:57.700 --> 00:22:01.030
even at four years.

00:22:01.030 --> 00:22:04.150
It's almost like you just put
your head down and, uh.

00:22:04.150 --> 00:22:05.980
DAN SCANLON: Luckily we'll have
plenty of time on Friday

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:07.470
afternoon to refresh
rotten tomatoes.

00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:11.360
KORI RAE: I'm not doing that.

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:13.950
MALE SPEAKER: I mean I
definitely haven't seen a film

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:16.400
where I've kind of like smiled
all the way through it.

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:18.730
It's just like a really
enjoyable film.

00:22:18.730 --> 00:22:21.310
Once you're into the world
and that's it.

00:22:21.310 --> 00:22:25.400
So I don't envision too many
bad reviews really.

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:28.980
Did you want to run the clip of
the ROR trailer because I

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:32.180
think it's interesting to talk
about the little different

00:22:32.180 --> 00:22:34.210
frat gangs that appear.

00:22:38.570 --> 00:22:40.470
Actually, there's like a real
opportunity to develop those

00:22:40.470 --> 00:22:43.180
different personalities and
characters within that.

00:22:43.180 --> 00:22:46.020
Is that based on the frat
gangs where you

00:22:46.020 --> 00:22:46.780
were growing up?

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:48.310
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, I mean I
think some of it is based on

00:22:48.310 --> 00:22:50.630
our own experiences and then
just sort of those classic

00:22:50.630 --> 00:22:54.450
college archetypes with the
monster twist on them.

00:22:54.450 --> 00:22:56.490
But yeah, I mean that was the
fun of having the fraternities

00:22:56.490 --> 00:23:00.090
and sororities in the movie,
was to be able to just

00:23:00.090 --> 00:23:01.850
celebrate those kind of classic

00:23:01.850 --> 00:23:04.630
college cliches and types.

00:23:04.630 --> 00:23:05.790
MALE SPEAKER: I love the
guy with the lisp.

