MALE SPEAKER: I did used to
hear Pixar stories that

00:23:08.940 --> 00:23:11.650
occasionally some of the traits
of animators or people

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:14.660
that work there found their
way into the characters.

00:23:14.660 --> 00:23:16.470
No one at Pixar with a lisp?

00:23:16.470 --> 00:23:19.220
DAN SCANLON: No, not
that I would say.

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:19.440
KORI RAE: No.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:22.090
But I think Bobby Moynihan
who voiced the character

00:23:22.090 --> 00:23:23.530
of Chet kind of--

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:24.310
DAN SCANLON: He adds a lot.

00:23:24.310 --> 00:23:25.150
KORI RAE: He adds
a lot to that.

00:23:25.150 --> 00:23:26.310
He came up with that I think.

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:29.845
I mean you directed it, but
it's kind of his thing.

00:23:29.845 --> 00:23:31.420
He's so great.

00:23:31.420 --> 00:23:34.040
MALE SPEAKER: So now the
film is finished.

00:23:34.040 --> 00:23:36.700
You get this chance to maybe
take a bit of a breather

00:23:36.700 --> 00:23:40.450
before you begin to sort of
build up the energy to take on

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:41.170
something else.

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:42.805
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, absolutely.

00:23:42.805 --> 00:23:44.380
I'm going to take
some time off.

00:23:44.380 --> 00:23:44.870
KORI RAE: Exactly.

00:23:44.870 --> 00:23:46.580
A little bit.

00:23:46.580 --> 00:23:46.930
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:23:46.930 --> 00:23:48.890
KORI RAE: And then, yeah, come
back and then we'll go into

00:23:48.890 --> 00:23:53.863
development and see if we can
come up with another idea--

00:23:53.863 --> 00:23:54.570
MALE SPEAKER: That's
fantastic.

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:55.120
KORI RAE: --for another movie.

00:23:55.120 --> 00:23:55.550
Yeah.

00:23:55.550 --> 00:23:58.150
MALE SPEAKER: In terms of
questions we only have sort of

00:23:58.150 --> 00:23:59.350
15-20 minutes left.

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:04.580
So if anyone would like to cue
up that would be fantastic.

00:24:07.570 --> 00:24:10.050
AUDIENCE: I read that this is
the first Pixar movie that

00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:12.300
makes full use so ray tracing?

00:24:12.300 --> 00:24:15.870
I'm wondering if you could
discuss how that affected the

00:24:15.870 --> 00:24:19.640
creative process with
movie making?

00:24:19.640 --> 00:24:20.680
KORI RAE: Yeah, I mean yeah.

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:25.133
Global illumination and that--
we've kind of did a bunch of R

00:24:25.133 --> 00:24:25.900
&amp; D at the beginning.

00:24:25.900 --> 00:24:29.436
And we've used that for the
first time on this film.

00:24:29.436 --> 00:24:30.850
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, and
it's beautiful.

00:24:30.850 --> 00:24:32.430
I mean we love the look of it.

00:24:32.430 --> 00:24:35.130
It works really well for
this particular film.

00:24:35.130 --> 00:24:40.160
It allows us to, or it allowed
me to see scenes lit kind of

00:24:40.160 --> 00:24:42.680
quicker and more specifically.

00:24:42.680 --> 00:24:46.000
Which allowed us to tell a story
with light in a way that

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.220
we really wanted to do.

00:24:49.220 --> 00:24:53.630
Which just makes everything
easier I felt.

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:57.780
And Pete Docter was the
executive producer on this

00:24:57.780 --> 00:25:01.090
film and he was a big mentor
for me the whole time.

00:25:01.090 --> 00:25:04.450
And he would come in, and once
a week, and look at character

00:25:04.450 --> 00:25:07.130
designs and animation.

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:10.250
And it had been 12 years since
he did his film and they did

00:25:10.250 --> 00:25:11.880
it on a Texas Instrument
computer.

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:16.490
He would look at what I
get to see and he'd

00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:17.980
go, you're so lucky.

00:25:17.980 --> 00:25:19.650
You have it so easy.

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:21.660
When he would see character
designs they were sort of

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:25.720
frozen in this weird shape and
made out of simple things.

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:28.740
And I'd see them they'd be posed
in a production pose

00:25:28.740 --> 00:25:30.180
with a drop shadow on it.

00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:32.290
I'm like sure, that
looks good.

00:25:32.290 --> 00:25:33.000
So easy.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:33.905
Sorry.

00:25:33.905 --> 00:25:35.360
KORI RAE: That's true.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:35.652
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:25:35.652 --> 00:25:37.450
Thanks so much for coming.

00:25:37.450 --> 00:25:39.790
So the past three out of four
Pixar movies have been either

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:41.430
sequels or prequels.

00:25:41.430 --> 00:25:44.580
So my question is why, and what
are the challenges of

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:46.220
coming up with new stories
when there's

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:48.736
already existing material?

00:25:48.736 --> 00:25:53.140
KORI RAE: Yeah, I mean we're
kind of lucky to be able to

00:25:53.140 --> 00:25:55.970
make more movies than
we could years ago.

00:25:55.970 --> 00:25:58.810
And we're able to go back into
these worlds and tell new

00:25:58.810 --> 00:26:02.990
stories with existing characters
and worlds that we

00:26:02.990 --> 00:26:03.830
created a while ago.

00:26:03.830 --> 00:26:06.500
So we're actually excited
to go back into a

00:26:06.500 --> 00:26:07.250
lot of these worlds.

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:09.460
And we're also excited to
tell original stories.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:12.040
We're just happy to
be doing both.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:14.500
But I think certainly
sequels and prequels

00:26:14.500 --> 00:26:16.150
offer another challenge.

00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:18.930
Because it's--

00:26:18.930 --> 00:26:25.150
you have to kind of deal with
predictability and everything

00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:29.640
that goes before, and come up
with brand new ideas that will

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:30.740
keep the audience interested.

00:26:30.740 --> 00:26:31.960
So it's challenging.

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:35.800
But I think we're really glad
that we're able to do both.

00:26:35.800 --> 00:26:37.330
And move forward doing both.

00:26:37.330 --> 00:26:39.090
DAN SCANLON: We finally
have that luxury.

00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:40.580
But sequels can be tough.

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:43.550
I mean we've said, it's like
it's as if someone took the

00:26:43.550 --> 00:26:46.670
game chess and said, OK use all
these pieces but come up

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:48.970
with a different game that's
just as good as chess but

00:26:48.970 --> 00:26:49.770
isn't chess.

00:26:49.770 --> 00:26:51.980
But you can't change the
characters that much.

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:53.430
It's this other challenge.

00:26:56.210 --> 00:26:57.460
AUDIENCE: This kind of
goes back to that

00:26:57.460 --> 00:26:58.660
pressure question earlier.

00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:01.990
So it seems like the tradition
that Pixar staff, co-directors

00:27:01.990 --> 00:27:04.660
of past feature films or short
films, step into director's

00:27:04.660 --> 00:27:06.710
chair such as Pete and Andrew.

00:27:06.710 --> 00:27:10.120
So how much did co-directing
that short film for "Cars"

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:12.800
help you step into the
director's chair this time?

00:27:12.800 --> 00:27:15.800
And also what does that say
about Pixar to have that much

00:27:15.800 --> 00:27:18.750
trust and confidence in somebody
with their immaculate

00:27:18.750 --> 00:27:19.370
track record?

00:27:19.370 --> 00:27:21.251
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:27:21.251 --> 00:27:22.245
Jesus.

00:27:22.245 --> 00:27:25.330
Pressure you guys
are putting on.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:29.490
I co-directed "Mater and the
Ghost Site" which was a short

00:27:29.490 --> 00:27:31.790
on the DVD several years ago.

00:27:31.790 --> 00:27:33.810
But with John, so I mean
you couldn't really

00:27:33.810 --> 00:27:36.570
have a better teacher.

00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:39.000
It's different than making
an original short.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:43.160
Those shorts, by the time we
do those, the whole team

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:45.150
you're with are so good
in that world.

00:27:45.150 --> 00:27:46.870
And the animators know how to
animate those characters.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:49.330
That ship kind of
sails itself.

00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:52.810
It's a really great jumping off
point, but it is a whole

00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:55.350
different world than
making a feature.

00:27:55.350 --> 00:27:58.010
I mean most the assets
already exist.

00:27:58.010 --> 00:27:59.740
I think we made a
lamp for that.

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:01.380
That was like the only
thing we made.

00:28:01.380 --> 00:28:03.550
I look back on it a little bit,
I was probably strutting

00:28:03.550 --> 00:28:07.140
around going, I co-directed a
movie, and not realizing, no

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:08.690
you didn't.

00:28:08.690 --> 00:28:11.960
You kind of did, but yeah.

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:16.640
But I actually think that more
the years in story are where

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:17.850
the trust comes from.

00:28:17.850 --> 00:28:20.920
Because story is the most
important thing when directing

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:22.630
a movie because all
your decisions

00:28:22.630 --> 00:28:23.895
go back to the story.

00:28:23.895 --> 00:28:26.820
You don't have to know
everything about animation, or

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.260
lighting, or how the
computer works.

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:32.210
You just have to know how to
explain the emotions that you

00:28:32.210 --> 00:28:34.940
want and to know how
to tell a story.

00:28:34.940 --> 00:28:37.490
So I think actually making the
feature film I made on my own

00:28:37.490 --> 00:28:39.370
was probably where more of
the trust came from.

00:28:39.370 --> 00:28:42.970
Because that was something
that they made that was a

00:28:42.970 --> 00:28:46.700
feature-length project.

