Humble brag.

00:29:18.580 --> 00:29:19.870
DAN SCANLON: It's no big
deal, been to Europe.

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:20.650
KORI RAE: Oh that's
bragging, really?

00:29:20.650 --> 00:29:21.880
Shit.

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:25.020
Anyhow, but so I'm not sure
what's happening with it.

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:27.960
But I would imagine that they're
going to put some cool

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:28.910
new stuff on there I hope.

00:29:28.910 --> 00:29:30.354
It is great, I love it.

00:29:30.354 --> 00:29:31.740
DAN SCANLON: Yeah, me too.

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:34.430
AUDIENCE: Along the lines of
the sequel, prequel, I was

00:29:34.430 --> 00:29:37.170
surprised when I looked up that
the original movie came

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:38.550
out in 2001.

00:29:38.550 --> 00:29:41.760
And so I think about how much
changed in my life since that

00:29:41.760 --> 00:29:44.270
time, because I was in high
school when it came out.

00:29:44.270 --> 00:29:48.520
So what is the challenge when
you take for instance that

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:51.210
large amount of time between
audiences and maybe some of

00:29:51.210 --> 00:29:54.340
the original viewers are now
going into college themselves.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:57.410
And then as a quick follow-up
is there a door open for a

00:29:57.410 --> 00:30:00.360
return of Mike and
Sully after this?

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:05.140
KORI RAE: Yeah, I mean I think
the fact that it's 12 years

00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:09.070
later and a lot of kids were
six or seven when they saw

00:30:09.070 --> 00:30:11.320
"Monsters Inc" and are
now going to college.

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:13.920
That totally is a
happy accident.

00:30:13.920 --> 00:30:18.240
I know that probably sounds
like a lie but it's not.

00:30:18.240 --> 00:30:21.170
It really was the timing
did work out that way.

00:30:21.170 --> 00:30:23.760
We didn't even know what the
release date of the movie

00:30:23.760 --> 00:30:26.180
would be when we started
talking about it.

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:28.750
That was really a happy accident
that's been fun.

00:30:28.750 --> 00:30:31.790
I mean we did a lot of
screenings at colleges and

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:33.180
universities around
the country.

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:37.510
And it was really fantastic to
see the feedback just of kids

00:30:37.510 --> 00:30:40.620
who kind of grew up with
Mike and Sully and

00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:41.870
now they're at school.

00:30:41.870 --> 00:30:43.920
DAN SCANLON: And we're going
to wait another 60 years to

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:47.810
make "Monsters Retirement Home"
so that you can all

00:30:47.810 --> 00:30:49.240
relate to that.

00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:53.200
We really don't have any idea
for what happens next.

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:54.520
We don't know yet.

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:54.680
KORI RAE: Yeah.

00:30:54.680 --> 00:30:55.350
DAN SCANLON: Or if.

00:30:55.350 --> 00:30:57.270
KORI RAE: No plans yet.

00:30:57.270 --> 00:31:01.320
AUDIENCE: Is this is the first
G rated college movie?

00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:01.780
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:03.490
AUDIENCE: Was that like
a good challenge or?

00:31:03.490 --> 00:31:04.320
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:08.280
It is, I mean it is, for
the obvious reasons.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:11.090
But we realized early on that
what John Lasseter called kind

00:31:11.090 --> 00:31:14.270
of the raucous nature of
college, as long as you had

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:17.650
monsters kind of falling down
and smashing things and eating

00:31:17.650 --> 00:31:18.930
garbage out of the
garbage can.

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:21.720
It kind of felt like, oh that's
a pretty wild party.

00:31:21.720 --> 00:31:25.130
I don't need to know what's in
the red cup, although there

00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:26.380
are red cups.

00:31:29.910 --> 00:31:30.930
But you know what?

00:31:30.930 --> 00:31:34.400
In some ways though, I think
the bigger issue was that

00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:36.270
college is what college
movies are about.

00:31:36.270 --> 00:31:39.410
And I think that was a tougher
sell in a way.

00:31:39.410 --> 00:31:42.440
College movies are about
rebellion and rebelling

00:31:42.440 --> 00:31:43.750
against the system.

00:31:43.750 --> 00:31:46.960
And without giving anything
away, I mean these guys do

00:31:46.960 --> 00:31:48.150
that a lot.

00:31:48.150 --> 00:31:52.540
They have to, and it has to be
about kind of bucking the

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:53.290
system a little bit.

00:31:53.290 --> 00:31:57.110
And I almost feel like that is
more subversive and harder for

00:31:57.110 --> 00:32:00.590
people to swallow because yeah,
a college movie for

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:03.160
parents would be about kids
that go to school and do

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:05.950
great, and get great grades, and
don't have any problems.

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:08.120
And this can't be that.

00:32:08.120 --> 00:32:09.370
KORI RAE: Right.

00:32:11.805 --> 00:32:13.430
AUDIENCE: This is a
question for Dan.

00:32:13.430 --> 00:32:16.660
You mentioned earlier and then
you alluded to it in your

00:32:16.660 --> 00:32:20.180
career path, that you made this
movie on your spare time

00:32:20.180 --> 00:32:21.210
with other Pixar people?

00:32:21.210 --> 00:32:23.550
I wonder if you could tell a
little more of that within the

00:32:23.550 --> 00:32:25.120
context of Pixar culture?

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:28.110
Like are there always these
creative ambitious people

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:29.450
doing these side projects?

00:32:29.450 --> 00:32:31.880
Or where you really like driven
to figure out how you

00:32:31.880 --> 00:32:34.150
could kind of take your career
to the next level?

00:32:34.150 --> 00:32:36.170
DAN SCANLON: Oh I think that's
what's great about Pixar is

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:37.190
there's a lot of people
doing that.

00:32:37.190 --> 00:32:37.610
KORI RAE: Yeah.

00:32:37.610 --> 00:32:39.950
DAN SCANLON: There's always
artists making their own comic

00:32:39.950 --> 00:32:41.550
book and people doing
their own thing.

00:32:41.550 --> 00:32:45.570
And I think Pixar is really
supportive of it, as long as

00:32:45.570 --> 00:32:48.140
it's handled correctly.

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:52.220
Because it's all about like
here, it's all about allowing

00:32:52.220 --> 00:32:54.010
people to get better
and explore.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:58.780
And what better way than for
them to do it on their own

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:01.310
little bit too.

00:33:01.310 --> 00:33:03.840
I think a lot of people are
doing those kinds of things

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:06.420
and it does help you grow.

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:08.640
AUDIENCE: With both of you
having been with Pixar since

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.840
before the Disney acquisition
and afterwards and with the

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:15.130
purchase of the "Star Wars"
franchise ringing in our ears,

00:33:15.130 --> 00:33:18.280
what kind of freedoms and how
did the production process and

00:33:18.280 --> 00:33:20.580
creative process change pre
and post acquisition?

00:33:23.230 --> 00:33:28.560
KORI RAE: I mean obviously the
biggest thing was access to

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:33.220
the characters and making more
films, sequels, prequels with

00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:33.820
those characters.

00:33:33.820 --> 00:33:37.220
That was kind of the biggest win
for us because we really

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:40.020
wanted to be able to do that.

00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:46.230
But creatively in terms of being
there, we're still so

00:33:46.230 --> 00:33:47.660
singularly focused--

00:33:47.660 --> 00:33:49.300
I can't say that word--

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:53.990
on just making great movies that
we haven't noticed any

00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:55.240
big changes.

00:33:55.240 --> 00:33:58.350
I mean when we're heads down
making a movie it's the same.

00:33:58.350 --> 00:34:02.240
We're trying to do better each
time and we're trying to tell

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:04.590
better stories and use
technology in a different way.

00:34:04.590 --> 00:34:08.725
But in terms of the culture
nothing has changed honestly.

00:34:12.232 --> 00:34:13.010
It's been good in that way.

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:14.139
DAN SCANLON: We're
a bigger company.

00:34:14.139 --> 00:34:15.179
KORI RAE: We're pretty
autonomous.

00:34:15.179 --> 00:34:19.170
I mean Pixar itself is an
autonomous part of the Disney

00:34:19.170 --> 00:34:19.850
corporation.

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:23.940
So, and it does feel
like that still.

00:34:23.940 --> 00:34:26.929
AUDIENCE: Pixar is known for
having great technical prowess

00:34:26.929 --> 00:34:28.630
and then also artistic vision.

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:30.830
So you have these two groups
of people with really

00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:31.520
incredible talent.

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:35.170
How do they match up against
one another where you have

00:34:35.170 --> 00:34:37.394
people able to do something but
necessarily not having the

00:34:37.394 --> 00:34:38.130
vision there.

00:34:38.130 --> 00:34:39.650
Or you have people having
the vision but not

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:42.070
the technical ability.

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:42.510
KORI RAE: Yeah.

00:34:42.510 --> 00:34:44.719
I mean I think that is
one of the beautiful

00:34:44.719 --> 00:34:45.639
things about Pixar.

00:34:45.639 --> 00:34:49.790
It was started by John Lasseter
and Bill Reeves,

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:51.210
sitting in a room together--

00:34:51.210 --> 00:34:53.860
the artist and then the
technical director.

00:34:53.860 --> 00:34:56.719
Kind of sitting there helping
each other solve problems,

00:34:56.719 --> 00:34:58.810
creative problems and
technical problems.

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:03.490
And I think that's kind of the
basis of what Pixar what we

00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:04.860
were built on.

00:35:04.860 --> 00:35:07.100
With kind of that mentality.

00:35:07.100 --> 00:35:11.450
So we work really hard to make
sure that that those people do

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:12.120
collaborate.

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:16.490
I mean we have the folks who
are building the characters

00:35:16.490 --> 00:35:19.440
and rigging the characters
really in the same room with

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:22.870
the animators to figure
out how best to do it.

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:26.090
And the best shows and the best
departments and the best

00:35:26.090 --> 00:35:29.220
movies are the ones who do that
collaboration the best.

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:30.760
And you have to have it.

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:34.580
It's so key because these
films are exactly that.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:37.490
It is a true marriage of
art and technology.

00:35:37.490 --> 00:35:39.870
And you have to have
that collaboration.

00:35:39.870 --> 00:35:43.340
And so a lot of my job as a
producer is actually to make

00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:44.400
sure that that's happening.

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:47.510
And that it's happening in all
departments and that all

00:35:47.510 --> 00:35:50.460
departments are talking
to one another.

00:35:50.460 --> 00:35:55.260
So it's really important and it
requires a fair bit of work

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:57.950
and to make sure that
we keep doing that.

00:35:57.950 --> 00:36:00.860
DAN SCANLON: And Kori really
made that happen on this film.

00:36:00.860 --> 00:36:07.280
It was a big part of what you
brought to the film is that

00:36:07.280 --> 00:36:08.020
working together.

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:11.500
I feel like we really had
departments working together

00:36:11.500 --> 00:36:13.130
in such a special way
on this film.

00:36:13.130 --> 00:36:15.986
And I think it shows
in the final film.

00:36:15.986 --> 00:36:16.890
KORI RAE: Cool.

00:36:16.890 --> 00:36:17.530
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:36:17.530 --> 00:36:19.000
This is such a treat.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.190
Your movies have such attention
to detail, and after

00:36:22.190 --> 00:36:25.590
five years and that amount of
focus are there still things

00:36:25.590 --> 00:36:28.830
that you look at and you say
I wish wed done this?

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:31.990
Or do you get to do
get to do it all?

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:33.970
DAN SCANLON: Boy, I gotta say
with five years you kind of

00:36:33.970 --> 00:36:34.850
get to do it all.

00:36:34.850 --> 00:36:39.700
Like sometimes almost to
a nightmarish degree.

00:36:39.700 --> 00:36:43.180
You watch each shot so many
times with a room full of

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:45.375
people looking for the tiniest
little mistake.

00:36:48.420 --> 00:36:51.100
It's not that I'm saying the
movie's perfect or anything,

00:36:51.100 --> 00:36:54.600
but as far as those details
really everybody

00:36:54.600 --> 00:36:55.980
just combs over them.

00:36:55.980 --> 00:36:58.560
Although it is funny, Leon Kirch
told me, he said, wait

00:36:58.560 --> 00:36:59.900
til the movie comes
out though.

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:01.260
People will find stuff.

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:03.670
But we were in a room full
of people looking at

00:37:03.670 --> 00:37:05.600
every little dot.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:08.390
And he's like, they'll find
something and it will be huge

00:37:08.390 --> 00:37:12.580
because you were so busy looking
at the one frame that

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:16.690
turned off for a frame, that
you'll miss the fact that he

00:37:16.690 --> 00:37:18.030
said in "Toy Story 3"--

00:37:18.030 --> 00:37:20.110
I don't think he'll mind-- he
said in "Toy Story 3" somebody

00:37:20.110 --> 00:37:22.470
pointed out that at one point
Andy is running around with

00:37:22.470 --> 00:37:23.580
Woody or something.

00:37:23.580 --> 00:37:26.980
And the camera pans over-- the
entire bed is shoved halfway

00:37:26.980 --> 00:37:27.810
into the wall.

00:37:27.810 --> 00:37:31.890
And he's like, we watched this a
million times and called out

00:37:31.890 --> 00:37:34.180
the tiniest little stuff
and we missed that.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:37.840
So keep an eye out for
our giant mistakes.

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:40.790
KORI RAE: Yeah, that's true.

00:37:40.790 --> 00:37:42.400
MALE SPEAKER: Well it's
interesting about the

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.870
communication thing a little
bit because I know the

00:37:44.870 --> 00:37:48.770
original atrium at Pixar was
built so that everyone could

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:52.690
meet, eat together, bump into
each other and exchange ideas.

00:37:52.690 --> 00:37:56.000
And now it's a far bigger
company in a way.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.900
Does that still happen or is it
a case of sort of making a

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:02.260
point of leaving your office,
walking around, and

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:02.880
interrupting?

00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:04.590
KORI RAE: No, it really
does still happen.

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:06.190
And the bathrooms--

00:38:06.190 --> 00:38:06.730
that's the key.

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:08.930
It's the food but it's
also the restrooms.

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:10.260
That's where you meet people.

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:15.040
And Steve insisted on putting
them all in the middle, and we

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:17.430
when we were about to move into
the Emeryville campus

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:19.650
from Point Richmond we
were just up in arms.

00:38:19.650 --> 00:38:24.220
Like we can't walk that
far to the restroom.

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:27.260
But it actually works.

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:29.180
Well we have a few buildings--

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:32.750
each building is kind
of set up that way.

00:38:32.750 --> 00:38:34.440
It really does work.

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:36.690
At the very beginning of
this film we were in an

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.380
out-building kind of down an
alley a little away, when we

00:38:39.380 --> 00:38:40.790
were in early development.

00:38:40.790 --> 00:38:43.460
And we remember the difference
in moving

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:46.370
back to the main building.

00:38:46.370 --> 00:38:48.640
How great it was to see
everybody again.

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:51.290
And not be isolated like that.

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:52.860
So it is really important.

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:57.790
You run into people all the
time and it makes you

00:38:57.790 --> 00:39:00.230
communicate and talk to people
that you otherwise

00:39:00.230 --> 00:39:01.380
wouldn't have seen.

00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:03.560
So it's quite effective.

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:04.854
Steve's a smart guy.

00:39:04.854 --> 00:39:06.750
DAN SCANLON: Yeah.

00:39:06.750 --> 00:39:12.750
MALE SPEAKER: I guess we talk a
little bit about Steve, that

00:39:12.750 --> 00:39:14.390
things must have changed
a little from

00:39:14.390 --> 00:39:16.380
that aspect as well.

00:39:16.380 --> 00:39:19.580
And also with John because now
he's overseeing feature

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:22.160
animation down in LA.

00:39:22.160 --> 00:39:24.020
And then he still manages to--

00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:25.830
what's his working day like?

00:39:25.830 --> 00:39:26.650
It must be incredible.

00:39:26.650 --> 00:39:27.430
KORI RAE: Yeah it's crazy.

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:29.250
He's Superman for sure.

00:39:29.250 --> 00:39:32.300
None of us really quite
know how he does it.

00:39:32.300 --> 00:39:33.000
But he does.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:34.060
DAN SCANLON: He does
do it, yeah.

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:34.900
KORI RAE: And he's hands on.

00:39:34.900 --> 00:39:37.970
It's not like he's just coming
in and-- he's actively working

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:40.860
on all of the films and the
shorts and everything at the

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:43.160
studio every day.

00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:46.160
I think he goes down
to Disney one day a

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:49.070
week or two days sometimes.

00:39:49.070 --> 00:39:52.420
But yeah, we checked in with
him at least once a week,

00:39:52.420 --> 00:39:55.540
sometimes twice a week, for a
couple of hours and showed him

00:39:55.540 --> 00:39:57.510
all stages of production.

00:39:57.510 --> 00:40:01.250
Because it's really important
to get his genius eye on

00:40:01.250 --> 00:40:04.350
things and to get feedback
from him.

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:06.830
DAN SCANLON: He gives
great notes.

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.790
Because he has a distance from
it too that he can really

00:40:09.790 --> 00:40:12.020
judge because we've
been so focused.

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:13.420
KORI RAE: Right.

00:40:13.420 --> 00:40:15.370
MALE SPEAKER: I did also notice
that there was a recent

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:17.260
announcement that there's
going to be a lot more

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:19.290
features up til 2016.

00:40:19.290 --> 00:40:23.265
And films such as "Untitled Film
Number 8," "Untitled Film

00:40:23.265 --> 00:40:28.120
Number 9." So do you think one
of those may be yours, or you

00:40:28.120 --> 00:40:31.110
hope so, or you'll pitch a new
idea, what will you do?

00:40:31.110 --> 00:40:32.000
KORI RAE: Wait, what year?

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:32.920
DAN SCANLON: I don't know.

00:40:32.920 --> 00:40:33.800
We'll do the math.

00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:34.410
Well let's see.

00:40:34.410 --> 00:40:35.660
A year-long vacation.

00:40:38.340 --> 00:40:39.770
We don't know yet.

00:40:39.770 --> 00:40:41.870
We'll have to see, hopefully.

00:40:41.870 --> 00:40:45.470
KORI RAE: Yeah there's a
lot of stuff going on.

00:40:45.470 --> 00:40:47.210
And it's really--

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:49.860
we have a lot of projects in the
works and then you have to

00:40:49.860 --> 00:40:51.020
see how they pan out.

00:40:51.020 --> 00:40:53.910
Because even when you try
scheduling them and say, yeah,

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:56.390
we want this one to
come out here.

00:40:56.390 --> 00:40:58.450
Until you get really into it
you're not sure that it's

00:40:58.450 --> 00:40:59.360
going to work at all.

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:04.230
So there's a lot of shuffling
that happens before that.

00:41:04.230 --> 00:41:06.720
MALE SPEAKER: And sounds as if
that the pitching of an idea--

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:09.330
I kind of got the impression, is
it true that there's three

00:41:09.330 --> 00:41:10.840
ideas that you would
take to John?

00:41:10.840 --> 00:41:13.620
Particularly if you were going
to work on a short idea for a

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:17.220
movie, that you would approach
the brain trust with three

00:41:17.220 --> 00:41:20.660
strong ideas and then possibly
one of those may make it?

00:41:20.660 --> 00:41:22.440
Is that true?

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:23.080
KORI RAE: Yeah.

00:41:23.080 --> 00:41:24.890
That is, especially
the shorts.

00:41:24.890 --> 00:41:26.880
I think that is definitely
how.

00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:30.190
And I think it was a suggestion
from John because

00:41:30.190 --> 00:41:31.650
it just opens the world
a little more.

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:35.580
And I think they get to see
more of the creative of an

00:41:35.580 --> 00:41:36.400
individual.

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:37.240
If they're not--

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:39.690
if these aren't folks who've
directed before or something

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:42.230
and are coming out of
animation or story.

00:41:42.230 --> 00:41:47.040
It gives them a wider view of
the total creativity of the

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:49.110
person, to kind of pitch
three ideas.

00:41:49.110 --> 00:41:51.110
But it has been successful.

00:41:51.110 --> 00:41:52.160
DAN SCANLON: And you're not
putting all your eggs in one

00:41:52.160 --> 00:41:52.655
basket too.

00:41:52.655 --> 00:41:54.080
KORI RAE: Exactly, exactly.

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:55.480
MALE SPEAKER: We've got time
for two more questions.

00:41:55.480 --> 00:41:56.100
Is that OK?

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:57.680
KORI RAE: Cool.

