DAN SCANLON: How do
they interact?

00:42:06.100 --> 00:42:08.190
KORI RAE: Mostly on the creative
front, getting

00:42:08.190 --> 00:42:10.250
feedback on the creative
front.

00:42:10.250 --> 00:42:13.210
DAN SCANLON: It's nice because
you can take a little break

00:42:13.210 --> 00:42:16.710
from your own movie and your own
problems and go watch the

00:42:16.710 --> 00:42:18.930
rough reels of one of the movies
that's coming out two

00:42:18.930 --> 00:42:20.510
years after you.

00:42:20.510 --> 00:42:24.240
And give notes, and
again share their

00:42:24.240 --> 00:42:25.680
problems for a moment.

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:28.240
And selfishly the thing that I
like about it, and I think a

00:42:28.240 --> 00:42:30.830
lot of the directors do, is
even as you are doing that

00:42:30.830 --> 00:42:33.330
there's a small part of your
brain going, does that make

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:34.220
sense for my movie?

00:42:34.220 --> 00:42:36.680
Like when someone says, is
you're hero really being

00:42:36.680 --> 00:42:38.310
challenge to the utmost
